author: iannorden
content:
> I feel like `((x / y) * y) + (x % y) == x` should always be true, and I *think* it is only true if you truncate on `/`?
<@!301186049323958275> This is true, based on my check. Not sure how relevent that is, though. Idk that we need to conform to `((x / y) * y) + (x % y) == x`  any more or less than we need to conform to the rules of euclidean division:
```
Given two integers a and b, with b  0, there exist unique integers q and r such that

a = bq + r
and
0  r < |b|
```
Surely there are theoretical advantages of euclidean division but idk enough to put those forward.

author: timbeiko
content: <@!740996787548061849> those seem to be pending transactions. They aren't included in blocks because their gas price is too low. They aren't really "congesting" anything on the network, aside from nodes' transaction pools. If you look at transactions _actually_ included in blocks, you'll see the vast majority have gas prices close to what EthGasStation recommends at a certain time (or higher, but not much lower): https://etherscan.io/txs?block=10641117
